Hospital Course:

The patient, a 43-year-old female, presented with severe cervical pain, numbness, and paresis of both arms following a simple activity. Physical examination on admission revealed significant brachial diparesis with distal and left impairment. Additional studies confirmed clinical suspicion of cervical medullary lesion.

Treatment:

The patient was treated with acetyl-salicyclic acid (ASA) and underwent intensive rehabilitation. Clinical evolution was favourable showing residual mainly distal brachial diparaesthesia, with amyotrophy and flexor tendency of the fingers on both hands. The left tricipital reflex was abolished, and mild bibrachial tacto-algesic hypoesthesia was reported.

Follow-up:

Cervical MRI performed after one month revealed myelomalacia and cavity formation at C3-C7.

Summary:

A 43-year-old woman was admitted to the hospital with intense cervical pain, numbness, and paresis of both arms. MRI showed a hyperintense intramedullary lesion at C3-C7, confirming cervical medullary lesion. The patient was treated with ASA and underwent intensive rehabilitation with favourable clinical evolution. Follow-up MRI after one month showed myelomalacia and cavity formation at C3-C7. Discharge diagnosis was cervical medullary lesion.

Discharge Summary:

Patient: 74-year-old Korean male.

Clinical Presentation:
During the dissection, bilateral variations of the digastric muscle were found in the patient. Subcutaneous tissue, fascia superficialis, and platysma were carefully removed from the submental region to expose the muscle.

Diagnosis:
Asymmetric variation of the digastric muscle was found, including the discovery of accessory anterior bellies, which were innervated by the mylohyoid nerve. The anterior and posterior bellies of the digastric muscles on both sides were normal.

Treatment:
No treatment was administered as this was a cadaveric dissection.

Hospital Course:
The patient was not hospitalized as this was a cadaveric dissection.

Follow-Up Care:
Not applicable as the patient was deceased.

Outcome and Prognosis:
Not applicable as the patient was deceased.

Summary:
The bilateral variations of the digastric muscle in a 74-year-old Korean male were investigated during a cadaveric dissection. Asymmetric variations were found, including accessory anterior bellies innervated by the mylohyoid nerve. Normal anterior and posterior bellies were observed on both sides. No treatment was administered. The patient was not hospitalized, and there is no need for follow-up care.

The patient visited the emergency room with a case of chills, headaches, and rhinorrhea. Six days later, the patient returned to the clinic with abdominal discomfort, diarrhea, and chills. Laboratory tests revealed a decrease in platelet count and an increase in CRP levels. The patient was admitted to our medical center for further evaluation. Blood cultures were negative, but subsequent molecular tests showed evidence of P. malariae. After an initial treatment with oral hydroxychloroquine, the patient experienced a recurrence of parasitemia, which was later treated with oral mefloquine. Subsequent tests showed no evidence of infection.

Diagnosis:
P. malariae

Treatment:
The patient was initially treated with oral hydroxychloroquine, followed by oral mefloquine for the recurrence of parasitemia.

Hospital Course:
The patient, a 67-year-old male with non-small-cell lung carcinoma, was admitted with a one-month history of pruritic rash on his head and upper extremities. He had previously received combination therapy with pemetrexed, carboplatin, and pembrolizumab, followed by pembrolizumab monotherapy. Physical examination revealed violaceous, scaly, erythematous plaques with surrounding erythema and pigmentation, measuring 1-2 cm in diameter, on the patient's scalp. Similar keratotic erythematous lesions were present on the dorsum of his hands and forearms. Dermoscopic examination of a scalp lesion showed a whitish area at the center of the lesion surrounded by dotted or linear hyperpigmentation. Skin biopsy revealed orthokeratotic hyperkeratosis and irregular acanthosis that formed a saw-tooth appearance with hypergranulosis. A lichenoid reaction characterized by liquefaction degeneration with prominent necrosis of individual keratinocytes and band-like lymphocytic infiltrates was also present.

Treatment:
The patient was treated for two weeks with topical corticosteroids which dramatically improved the rash.

Follow-up:
The patient was discharged and recommended to continue using the topical corticosteroids as prescribed. Close follow-up with his medical oncologist was scheduled for further evaluation and management.

Hospital Course:

The patient, a 36-year-old female, presented to the psychiatry OPD with complaints of low mood, anergia with easy fatigability, and disturbed sleep. She was diagnosed with severe depression without psychotic symptoms and was started on Fluoxetine. After experiencing inadequate response, she was tried on Venlafaxine and lithium, but still had partial or poor response in aspects of energy levels and easy fatigability. Eight months later, she developed dry cough and exertional dyspnea, and a Rheumatology consultation was sought.

Diagnosis:

On examination, the patient had skin tightening of the face and extremities bilaterally, as well as Raynaud's phenomenon. A diagnosis of systemic sclerosis was made. Her lung function study and HRCT showed signs of interstitial lung disease (NSIP pattern).

Treatment:

The patient was put on cyclophosphamide pulse therapy for six months for her condition. Despite this, her lung condition deteriorated over time, and she ultimately succumbed to respiratory failure within one year of diagnosis.

Discharge Summary:

Patient, a 36-year-old female, was diagnosed with severe depression without psychotic symptoms. Despite being treated with multiple medications, she had partial or poor response in aspects of energy levels and easy fatigability. During her hospital course, the patient was diagnosed with systemic sclerosis and ultimately succumbed to respiratory failure within one year of diagnosis.

Hospital Course:

The patient, a 62-year-old obese man with a 2-year history of intermittent pain in the right shoulder, was admitted with worsening pain and weakness in the right shoulder with the restriction of active shoulder motion. The patient had been treated with conservative treatment (acupuncture, physical therapy, and subacromial steroid injections), which provided short periods of relief.

Diagnosis:

A clinical evaluation revealed that the patient's right shoulder joint had a limited active range of motion. The patient had gouty tophi on the dorsal aspect of the bilateral great toe and extensor aspect of the bilateral elbows. Based on the findings of the biopsy, the patient was diagnosed with gouty arthritis of bilateral shoulder joints.

Treatment:

The patient was treated with etoricoxib and febuxostat. The patient refused surgical intervention and decided to continue receiving physical therapy and medication for symptom control. 

Follow-up:

After physical therapy and medication, the pain in the right shoulder diminished further but was not eliminated. The patient was advised to follow-up regularly with primary care physician and specialist.

Hospital Course Summary:

Patient admitted to our rehabilitation unit in May 2020 for diagnostic advice and interdisciplinary care due to persistent pain after a contusion of the left forefoot that had occurred 5 months earlier. Initial treatment consisted of medication, physiotherapy, and foot orthoses, but was not effective. The patient had adopted an avoidance step on the heel and the lateral edge of the foot to avoid any contact of the hallux with the ground. Further investigations revealed bone oedema of the first metatarsal, first phalanx and medial sesamoid accompanied by soft tissue swelling predominantly on the plantar side interpreted as the stigmata of the bone contusion. 

During clinical examination, the patient reported continuous pain, sensory disturbances with a neuropathic component, changes in temperature and color of the hallux, increased sweating, and oedema. The presence of unfavorable cognitive and affective factors such as high kinesiophobia and catastrophism, high anxiety, and moderate depressive symptoms were found on questionnaires. 

A diagnosis of CRPS of the foot limited to the first radius of the left forefoot was evoked. Further investigations were pursued due to the rarity of this situation, and the Budapest criterion 4 was met. Discharge instructions were provided to continue pain management and to follow up with outpatient rehabilitation services.

This is a summary of the hospital course of a 53-year-old female who was admitted for management of a urinary tract infection. 

History and Physical Exam: 

The patient presented with symptoms suggestive of a urinary tract infection and was started on nitrofurantoin. After two doses of nitrofurantoin, the patient developed a rash on her left breast. On examination, she had a sharply demarcated erythematous and excoriated rash on her left breast.

Medical History: 

The patient had a prior history of squamous cell carcinoma of the left breast treated with neoadjuvant carboplatin, paclitaxel, and anthracycline chemotherapy followed by surgery and subsequent whole breast radiation.

Diagnosis: 

The patient was diagnosed with RRD to nitrofurantoin.

Treatment: 

Nitrofurantoin was immediately discontinued, and the patient was prescribed oral trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole for three days. The patient's rash quickly resolved within one week.

Follow-Up: 

The patient was discharged and advised to follow up with her primary care physician. 

Prognosis: 

The prognosis is good, and the patient is expected to continue to recover without any complications.

Disposition: 

The patient was discharged home on oral trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole for three days.

Histological examination of the esophageal biopsies revealed multinucleated giant cells with intranuclear inclusion bodies, typical for Herpes Simplex Virus Esophagitis (HSE). 

Treatment:
She was given intravenous hydration and a high dose of proton-pump inhibitors, which resulted in a complete resolution of her symptoms within five days. No antiviral medications were administered. 

Hospital Course:
One month later, the patient had no difficulty with swallowing. An esophagogastroduodenoscopy showed the complete resolution of the lesions. At 41 weeks gestation, the patient delivered a healthy baby girl with no complications. 

Follow-up:
After 14 months of follow-up, both the patient and baby remained healthy.

After empirical antibiotic treatment, his culture and sensitivity tests were conducted, revealing the presence of B. pseudomallei and resulting in tailored antibiotic treatment of cefixime and ciprofloxacin.

The patient underwent a surgical abscess-draining, debridement, and application of total contact casting to relieve body weight of the diabetic ulcer. Over the course of his stay, he experienced a successful healing process with no indications of recurrence or relapse.

Diabetic Ulcer with B. pseudomallei infection

The patient is advised to continue with the prescribed medications and regular check-up with his physician. He is to maintain good hygiene, keep the wound clean, and seek medical attention should there be any signs of recurrence or relapse.

Diagnosis:

Treatment:
The patient underwent a successful Cisplatin–Etoposide neoadjuvant chemotherapy regimen, and the lymphadenopathy reduced by 50% at three months of follow-up.

Two days prior to admission, the patient experienced a half-hour episode of panic, screaming, and babbling associated with dizziness and headaches.

The patient's neurodevelopment was normal, and there were no signs of regression or dysmorphic features. Cranial nerve examination findings were normal as well.

Hospital Course:

The patient was admitted to the surgery department following extravasation during barium enema. The patient presented with nausea, vomiting and intermittent abdominal cramping pain. On physical examination, the abdomen was distended and tender to palpation. Routine hematological and biochemical investigations were within normal limits except for a raised total leucocyte count.

Diagnostic Findings:

Plain X-ray of the abdomen revealed dilation of the rectum, sigmoid and descending colon with barium occupying the abdomen intraperitoneally. A chest X-ray did not reveal any pneumoperitoneum.

Treatment:

Immediate fluid resuscitation and intravenous antibiotics were initiated. An exploratory laparotomy revealed a perforation of the colon with barium covering the colon segments and omentum. Abdominal washout was performed followed by sigmoid colon resection with Mikulicz colostomy and omentectomy. Oral diet was resumed on the third postoperative day, and after complete recovery, the patient was discharged on the ninth day.

Follow-up:

The patient was discharged with a plan to close the colostomy 8 weeks later.

This patient, a 19-year-old female with a partially cystic brain stem tumor that was histologically diagnosed as pilocytic astrocytoma, was referred to us in February 2005 after two previous surgeries. The MRI revealed a recurrence of the large cystic tumor within the pons, with its solid portion extending down to the medulla oblongata.

Treatment:

The patient received gamma knife surgery, which focused only on the solid portion of the tumor. The tumor received 12Gy at the margin of the solid portion at 50% isodose curve. At 3 months clinical evaluation showed gradual general improvement. Last MRI done in October 2006 (22 months after GKS) showed marked reduction of the cystic part and even reduced in size of the solid portion.

Summary:

This patient, having undergone two previous surgeries for their partially cystic brainstem tumor, was referred to us for further treatment due to recurring symptoms. After gamma knife surgery, the patient's symptoms improved and follow-up MRI scans showed a marked reduction in the tumor's size. The patient was discharged in improved condition.

The patient presented with body weakness, dysphagia and dysarthria of 14 days duration. Upon admission, he was diagnosed with myasthenia gravis due to positive serum anti-acetylcholine receptor antibodies. Additionally, he was found to have autoimmune polyglandular syndrome based on low fasting cortisol levels, low TSH levels and high T3 and T4 levels. 

The patient received six sessions of plasmapheresis and was prescribed prednisolone, pyridostigmine, azathioprine, vitamin D and thyroxin. Additionally, physiotherapy was recommended. The patient showed improvement in muscle power after the third session of plasmapheresis and was able to walk independently after undergoing six sessions of physiotherapy. The NG tube was removed and the patient was started on a semi-solid diet after these sessions.

The patient was discharged after showing a good response to treatment. 

The final diagnosis for the patient was myasthenia gravis and autoimmune polyglandular syndrome.

Hospital Course Summary:

Admission:
A 57-year-old diabetic hypertensive man previously with a history of smoking was admitted for evaluation of chest pain.

History:
The patient had undergone a successful repair of aortic coarctation 21 years prior using balloon angioplasty. He presented with a gradual decline in his functional capacity and was found to have moderately dilated left ventricle with ejection fraction of 60%. Coronary angiography revealed left main disease at 70% and significant stenosis of the obtuse marginal and proximal right coronary artery.

Procedure:
On the day of surgery, the patient underwent a successful triple coronary artery bypass graft (CABG) with three saphenous vein grafts. Intraoperatively, the left internal mammary artery (LIMA) was revealed to be tortuous with absent palpable pulses. Histological examination of a segment of the left IMA revealed extensive atherosclerosis with prominent intimal fibrosis and calcification.

Follow-up:
The patient's follow-up was uneventful and is being treated with blood pressure-adjusted doses of beta blockers, angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors, and aldactone.

Discharge:
The patient was discharged in stable condition on the day following surgery. He was advised to continue medications as prescribed and to follow up as scheduled.

IDENTIFICATION:
Patient Name: [Redacted]
Gender: Female
Age: 83 years
Race: Japanese

HOSPITAL COURSE:
The patient presented with a 2cm elastic hard mass in the lower inner quadrant of the right breast. She was diagnosed with invasive papillary carcinoma following an ultrasonography-guided needle biopsy. The mammography revealed a dense mass with partially indistinct margins and the MRI scan showed a highly enhancing lesion. The patient declined surgery and opted for neoadjuvant endocrine therapy with Letrozole. After 12 months of Letrozole treatment, breast-conserving surgery was performed, showing fibrosis and elastosis. The patient was diagnosed with Pathologic Complete Response (pCR). No adjuvant radiotherapy was recommended considering the age and poor level of activities of daily living. 

DISCHARGE DIAGNOSIS:
 - Invasive papillary carcinoma in the right breast 
 - Fibrosis and elastosis following neoadjuvant endocrine therapy

DISCHARGE INSTRUCTIONS:
- Follow up with medical oncologist every 6 months for the next 2 years
- Continue Letrozole for the next 5 years 
- Annual mammogram and breast ultrasound monitoring are recommended

FOLLOW UP:
The patient is encouraged to follow up with a medical oncologist every 6 months for the next 2 years to ensure there are no signs of cancer recurrence. Annual mammograms and breast ultrasounds are also recommended. The patient should continue Letrozole for the next 5 years as per the neoadjuvant therapy regimen.

Gender: Male

Diagnosis: Granulomatous Inflammatory Process

Hospital Course:
The patient, a 60-year-old male, was admitted with a nodular lesion on his right leg that had been present for the last six months. His personal history revealed that he had previously been treated for multiple squamous cell carcinomas. The initial diagnostic hypothesis was subcutaneous mycosis, and the patient underwent complete lesion excision. The histopathological analysis revealed the presence of a granulomatous inflammatory process with sporangia identified on microscopic examination. The patient's wound was allowed to heal by secondary intention, and topical mupirocin and silver nitrate 10% were used for the same purpose.

Treatment:
The patient was treated with fluconazole 150 mg/day for three months until complete healing of the lesion.

Follow-up:
The patient is advised to follow a regular follow-up schedule with his healthcare provider to monitor his condition.

Conclusion:
In conclusion, the patient was diagnosed with granulomatous inflammatory process and underwent complete lesion excision, followed by three months of fluconazole therapy. The patient's wound healed well, and he is advised to follow-up regularly with his healthcare provider.

Hospital Course:
A 30-year-old female patient with a history of uveitis associated with ocular toxocariasis and bilateral LASIK 10 years previously, was admitted to the glaucoma clinic due to uncontrolled intraocular pressure (IOP). Despite maximally tolerable medical treatment, the IOP increased, and the patient required phacotrabeculectomy with topically applied mitomycin-C (0.04%).

Course Summary:
Postoperatively, the patient experienced transient hypotony with diffuse corneal edema and a cloudy flap interface. Spectral-domain optical coherence tomography (SD-OCT) scanning showed a diffuse and thin fluid pocket in the corneal interface region. However, after suture-lysis of the scleral flap and the use of brimonidine (0.2%)/timolol (0.5%), the edema resolved, and the IOP decreased significantly. The patient was discharged with no IOP-lowering agents and maintained IOP control with no recurrence of corneal edema or interface haze during the 8-month follow-up. The visual acuity improved to 20/100.

This discharge summary pertains to a 16-year-old female patient with a history of suprasellar disseminated juvenile pilocytic astrocytoma (JPA) treated 9 years prior with chemotherapy and craniospinal radiation.

The patient presented with a 1-day onset of headaches and vomiting and was diagnosed with a cerebellar mass with edema and compression of the 4th ventricle. Histopathologic analysis revealed an sGBM, characterized by pseudopalisading necrosis, vascular proliferation, and high mitotic index. This was markedly different from her initial diagnosis of JPA 9 years prior.

Postoperatively, the patient underwent treatment with a combination of therapies including reirradiation, temozolamide, bevacizumab, and everolimus. However, despite the treatment, the patient passed away 1 year post-diagnosis of sGBM and 10 years post her initial diagnosis of disseminated JPA.

Improvement in sensorium was observed over the next few hours. There was no subsequent recurrence, and he remained asymptomatic thereafter.

Hospital Course:
The patient was admitted to Kagoshima University Hospital with a complaint of epigastralgia. She was diagnosed with stage IV gastric cancer, and a gastrojejunostomy was produced in the middle third of her stomach to improve food passage. 

Treatment:
The patient was given a combination of S-1 and paclitaxel but the tumor regrew after four courses of chemotherapy. Chemoradiotherapy (CRT) was started for the purpose of local control, which resulted in marked tumor and nodal shrinkage. Then, distal gastrectomy with D2 lymphadenectomy was performed with curative intent.

Post-Operative Course:
The patient's postoperative course was uneventful, and she was followed closely without adjuvant therapy due to low white blood cell levels. Four years after the operation, she is well, and the tumor has not relapsed.

Conclusion:
Multidisciplinary treatment involving CRT might be useful as a second-line treatment for locally advanced gastric cancer. The modified Devine procedure seems to be suitable for stage IV gastric cancer patients planning to receive intensive chemotherapy and/or CRT.

HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS:
39-year-old Korean female presents with indigestion. She was diagnosed with iron deficiency anemia (IDA) 5 years ago and was taking iron supplements intermittently. She denies any past medical history or family history of gastrointestinal neoplasm. Laboratory examination showed IDA, and a gastrointestinal endoscopy was done.

HOSPITAL COURSE:
During the endoscopy, diffuse mucosal nodularity with a cobblestone appearance was observed. Biopsy was taken at the anterior aspect of the antrum, and H. pylori was found. H. pylori eradication was carried out, and follow-up endoscopy was done 4 weeks later. Cobblestone appearance was still noticed, and biopsy was negative for H. pylori or MALT lymphoma.

DIAGNOSIS:
Nodular gastritis without evidence of gastric MALT lymphoma-mimicking lesion after successful H. pylori eradication.

TREATMENT:
H. pylori eradication was carried out and regular iron supplements were taken for three months.

DISPOSITION:
The patient is now being followed up with an annual endoscopic examination plan at the outpatient department.

CONDITION AT DISCHARGE:
Patient is stable. Iron levels have improved.

FOLLOW-UP:
Annual endoscopic examination is recommended.

Medical History:
The patient had a history of diabetes, end-stage kidney disease on hemodialysis, spinal cord injury, and bilateral hemipelvectomy and lower-limb amputation.

The patient was admitted for septic shock from a sacral pressure ulcer infection. He received two cardiopulmonary resuscitation due to asphyxiation and hemoptysis-induced upper airway obstruction. A TIF was identified as the source of bleeding, which was sealed with an endovascular stent graft. Four days later, he underwent an anterior mediastinal tracheostomy.

Clinical Findings:
Computed tomography showed the right anterior location of the hemorrhage and adjacent anatomical location of the trachea and innominate artery.

Treatment:
An endovascular stent graft was placed from his right common carotid artery, sacrificing the right subclavian artery to seal the bleeding site.

Outcome:
The postoperative course was uneventful with no neurologic sequelae.

Instructions:
The patient is discharged and can resume his daily activities. He is advised to keep a close follow-up with his healthcare provider.

Hospital Course:
A 23-year-old woman presented with odynophagia and neck pain, exacerbated by food intake and neck movement. The patient was diagnosed with retropharyngeal abscess based on an initial evaluation, which was later revised to acute RCT following a CT scan. The patient was treated with analgesia and empirical antibiotics. The symptoms gradually improved, and the patient was discharged five days after admission. 

Discharge Diagnosis:
Acute RCT

Discharge Condition:
Stable

Discharge Medications:
None prescribed

Follow-Up Plans:
Two months after her discharge, the patient underwent a repeat lateral cervical radiograph and CT scan. These tests showed a resolution of retropharyngeal/prevertebral soft tissue edema, with minimal residual soft tissue calcification anterior to the odontoid process. The patient's ESR reduced to 20 mm/hr, indicating recovery. No further follow-up was deemed necessary.

Hospital Course Summary:

Patient 3, a 25-year-old female from Tay Ninh province, presented with fever, fatigue, cervical lymphadenopathy, and skin lesions. At presentation, she was diagnosed with HIV and T. marneffei infection. After being treated with itraconazole for two weeks, she was discharged in better condition. She began first-line ART on D+37 and was thriving until month 5 on ART when she developed a fever, new purulent skin lesions on her face and legs, and bilateral interphalangeal joint swelling and pain.

During her hospitalization, she underwent several diagnostic tests including abdominal ultrasound, chest X-ray, and sputum AFB smear, which confirmed her diagnosis of tuberculosis. She was then started on antituberculosis therapy with isoniazid, rifampicin, ethambutol, and pyrazinamide for which she was treated for 19 days before being discharged.

She was also treated for an MSSA super-infection of the skin lesions with intravenous amphotericin B deoxycholate and intravenous oxacillin for two weeks. She was also prescribed ibuprofen for joint pain.

The patient was discharged with a prescription of itraconazole for further 10 weeks to account for the rifampicin-induced reduction in itraconazole levels. At the last follow up visit in June 2016, she was completely well, and her CD4 T-cell count had increased to 170 cells/µL.

Hospital Course Summary:
A 68-year-old male with a history of coronary artery disease and ventral hernia repair presented with a non-healing abdominal wound. Imaging revealed the development of a subcutaneous abscess, which progressed to an enterocutaneous fistula. Bilateral cavitary nodules were identified on thoracic CT, and extensive microbiological investigations failed to identify a potential etiological agent for the patient's condition. A surgical biopsy revealed cutaneous ulcerations and inflammatory granulation tissue without dysplasia, leading to a diagnosis of an autoimmune disorder. The patient improved significantly after the initiation of an immunosuppressive regimen of corticosteroid and intravenous pulse cyclophosphamide. Surgical excision of the ECF with small bowel resection and anastomosis was performed after 2 months of immunosuppressive treatment, with control of an anastomotic leak with intra-abdominal drainage and antibiotic therapy. The patient was then discharged after a hospital stay of 143 days with close outpatient follow-up and treatment with azathioprine and decreasing doses of prednisone. No signs of ECF recurrence were noted 1 year after the episode of care.

Hospital Course:
The patient was admitted to our department with Furosemide-resistant ascites following a laparoscopic umbilical hernia repair. Diagnostic paracentesis revealed an exudate with an Ascites-to-Serum Lactate Dehydrogenase ratio of 0.74 and an Ascites-to-Serum Albumin ratio of 0.7. The fluid contained 730 cells/mL (38% lymphocytes, 23% neutrophils, 22% monocytes, 17% atypical). Gram stain and culture of ascitic fluid were negative.

Treatment:
The patient was managed with repeated large volume therapeutic paracentesis. Imatinib was discontinued for two weeks, resulting in spectacular arrest of ascites production. Subsequent reintroduction of imatinib at the same dose (600mg/day) was rapidly followed by recurrence of exudative ascites, requiring further therapeutic paracenteses. Again, pausing imatinib administration was effective in preventing ascites production. After two weeks, the drug was reintroduced at a low dose (200mg/day) escalating to a maintenance dose of 400mg/day over a period of a month without reappearance of ascites.

Outcomes:
The patient remains free of ascites two years later, while his chronic myeloid leukemia continues to be in major molecular remission. No other complications were reported.

Hospital Course:

This 55-year-old male patient presented with 30-year history of blood and blood clots in urine. The patient has been previously diagnosed with Glanzmann's thrombasthenia and has had a past craniotomy for evacuation of subdural hematoma. The patient has been experiencing recurrent episodes of epistaxis that have been managed conservatively.

During the last episode of hematuria a month ago, the patient experienced pain in the right loin. Imaging studies revealed the presence of a mid-ureteric calculus, which was subsequently managed using balloon dilatation. However, the guidewire used during the procedure accidentally perforated the interpole renal parenchyma. Hematuria persisted even after platelet and blood transfusions and Factor VIIa infusion.

Repeat ureteroscopy revealed inflamed ureteral mucosa and gross dilation of the ureter with large amounts of altered blood and blood clots. Laser lithotripsy was performed to fragment the stone, and a double-J stent was left in situ. However, bleeding persisted and a CT angiogram revealed the rupture of the artery supplying the interpole segment of the right kidney.

Angioembolization corrected the bleeding, and the patient was subsequently discharged with instructions to follow up with a urologist for further evaluation and management.

ground_truth.entity: rupture of the artery supplying the interpole segment of the right kidney

Hospital Course:

The patient, a 36-year-old male with rheumatoid arthritis, presented with holocranial headache that worsened with head mobilization and cough. He was previously diagnosed with a right lateral ventricle cyst that was obstructing the foramen of Monro with minimum ventricular dilatation and was under medical treatment. However, his symptoms worsened, and he underwent a neurosurgical evaluation.

Procedure:

The patient received a right ventricular endoscopic approach under general anesthesia. A large cyst obstructing the foramen of Monro was identified on the right ventricle, which was drained using a micro-scissor and 4F Fogarty catheter. Tissue and cyst content samples were sent for pathological evaluation, which showed a colloid cyst.

Course in Hospital:

The patient stayed in the ICU for one day and a total of three days in the hospital. He had completely recovered and was discharged after two months with normalized ventricular sizes and no cyst remaining. 

Recommendations:

The patient is advised to follow-up regularly with the neurosurgical team and continue the medical treatment for rheumatoid arthritis.

- Patient developed hypercapnia, dysphagia, and required mechanical ventilation with a tracheostomy.
- On day 15 of hospitalization, patient suffered a sudden cardiac arrest and was resuscitated with CPR.
- MRI showed diffuse hypoxic brain damage.
- Patient experienced two hypertensive attacks that were related to autonomic dysfunction and treated with diazepam and other antihypertensive medications.
- Patient's clinical symptoms improved significantly with treatment, and he displayed fewer hypertensive attacks over time.

- Patient will be discharged home with follow-up care instructions for ALS management.
- Arrangements for continued medical care and support will be made with the patient's primary healthcare provider.

The 67-year-old woman was admitted with recurrent dyspnea lasting for 2 weeks. She has a history of hypertension and has been receiving hemodialysis for the last 10 years. She was diagnosed with uraemic pleuropericarditis just 1 month ago and had been receiving intensive hemodialysis at our hospital. Physical examination and diagnostic testing revealed pleuropericarditis and pericardial effusion.

Treatment and Management:

The patient was treated with antibiotics and NSAIDs, but no significant improvement was observed. She required repeated thoracentesis and pericardiocentesis for relief of symptoms. A pleural biopsy was performed and thick fibrinous pleuritis was identified. Prednisolone therapy was administered, and the patient's symptoms abated within 1 week. Prednisolone was maintained at its initial dose for 36 days and tapered off by 10 mg a week.

Discharge:

The patient was discharged on the 71st hospital day without any symptoms. Throughout her hospitalization, she received on-line hemodiafiltration for 4 h, four to six times a week without using heparin. The patient's CRP level decreased from 6.08 mg/dL to 2.08 mg/dL. No pathogenic bacteria were isolated from her sputum and blood cultures, and serologic tests for various infections were negative.

A complete blood count, liver, and renal function tests, chest X-ray, and Mantoux tests were conducted, and the results were within normal limits. Her electroencephalogram showed periodic biphasic discharge at 1 Hz, and T2-weighted magnetic resonance imaging showed increased intensity in the right caudate nucleus and right lentiform nucleus. The final diagnosis was probable sCJD. 

Diagnosis: 
Probable sCJD 

Treatment:
Supportive care was provided, which included antiepileptics and antidepressants. 

Outcome:
The patient's condition progressively worsened during the hospital stay, and she passed away due to aspiration pneumonia 33 days after admission. 

Follow-Up:
No further follow-up was necessary.

Discharge Summary:

Patient: 62-year-old female with end-stage renal disease, hypertensive, and nondiabetic

Hospital Course:

The patient was admitted with a brachial artery aneurysm and underwent closure of arteriovenous fistula. Insertion of the left internal jugular vein tunneled catheter (TCC) was planned as the right IJV was not patent. After successful insertion, the patient developed a chyle leak, which was diagnosed with 99mTc-labeled nanocolloid lymphoscintigraphy and single-photon emission CT-CT (SPECT) correlation. Conservative treatment was administered as the catheter was a precious access and there were no potential veins for AVF. The chyle leak decreased slowly over several days, and during this time, the patient's blood pressure dropped. Treatment included fluid administration and high protein, low-fat diet.

Discharge Diagnosis:

Brachial artery aneurysm, end-stage renal disease, chyle leak, and hypertension.

Discharge Instructions:

The patient was advised to continue on a high protein, low-fat diet and to maintain regular outpatient follow-up. It was recommended that medical care providers monitor the patient's blood pressure and serum albumin levels in the future as well.

Discharge Summary:

Patient: 60-year-old male with locally advanced lung adenocarcinoma (cT2bN2M0-stage IIIA).

Hospital Course: The patient presented with muscle pain and blepharoptosis after receiving durvalumab as consolidation therapy for lung adenocarcinoma. Laboratory tests revealed elevated levels of serum creatine phosphokinase, aldolase, and lactate dehydrogenase. After being diagnosed with immune-related myositis (irMyositis), the patient was administered 1000 mg methylprednisolone daily for three days, followed by prednisolone 50 mg daily, which was tapered gradually. The patient's symptoms improved significantly, and his serum CK levels normalized. Durvalumab treatment was not resumed at the patient's request.

Summary: This is a 60-year-old male with a history of locally advanced lung adenocarcinoma who presented with muscle pain and blepharoptosis after receiving durvalumab as consolidation therapy. Laboratory tests revealed elevated levels of muscle enzymes, and the patient received a diagnosis of immune-related myositis. He was treated with steroids, which resulted in the normalization of his serum CK levels. Durvalumab treatment was not resumed at the patient's request. The patient did not show any signs of relapse of lung cancer until one year after discontinuation of durvalumab.

Discharge Summary:

Patient: 66-year-old Caucasian male

Admission Date: [Date of Admission]

Discharge Date: [Date of Discharge]

Hospital Course:

The patient was admitted for evaluation and management of an asymptomatic left buttock mass that was diagnosed to be metastatic Merkel cell carcinoma. His medical history includes prostate cancer (T1c). A computerized axial tomographic scan revealed the enlargement of lymph nodes and a soft tissue nodule in the left buttock. A PET/CT scan further confirmed the presence of a primary tumor in the left buttock.

Skin biopsy and immunohistochemical studies confirmed the diagnosis of metastatic Merkel cell carcinoma. The biopsy tissue was also sent for genomic evaluation, which revealed SUFU R299Q gene mutation. The patient was treated with carboplatin and etoposide. With the treatment, there was a decrease in the size of the left buttock tumor and lymph nodes.

After evaluation and management, the patient was discharged with the recommendation of adjuvant radiotherapy and consideration to use experimental agents if the tumor progresses.

Diagnosis: Metastatic Merkel cell carcinoma

Recommendations:

- Adjuvant radiotherapy
- Consideration of experimental agents if the tumor progresses

Follow-Up:

The patient is advised to have regular follow-up appointments with his healthcare provider to monitor the progression of the tumor and any new symptoms.

Hospital Course Summary:

Patient presented with recurrent complex partial seizures with secondary generalization, headache, and blurring of vision with diplopia. Examination revealed bilateral Grade 1 papilledema, facial deviation toward the left side, and left upper and lower limb power of 3/5. MRI showed a large T2 hypointense mass in the right temporal lobe with frond-like projections and perilesional edema. A small enhancing nodular lesion was also noted in the right frontal lobe. 

The patient underwent a right frontotemporal craniotomy and the mass and temporal lobe were excised, revealing CNS aspergillosis confirmed by microbiology. Treatment with Amphotericin B resulted in a drug reaction and hypokalemia, so voriconazole was started. The patient was discharged in a conscious and oriented state with persistent left hemiparesis and facial deviation. 

Follow-up care should include regular neurological evaluations and continuation of voriconazole treatment. The patient should receive education on how to manage their persistent left hemiparesis and facial deviation, and advised to report any concerning symptoms. Follow-up appointments with neurology and infectious disease specialties should also be scheduled.

The patient presented with pain and swelling in the left knee extending to the midthigh. Knee joint aspiration revealed the presence of white blood cells and red blood cells, but no crystals were identified in the synovial fluid. MRI results showed multiple cystic collections at the interfacial spaces of the hamstring muscles with significant edematous infiltration involving the soft tissue of the thigh and calf posteriorly. These findings were consistent with a perforated cyst that leaked its content into the surrounding soft tissue. 

Treatment:

The patient received an intra-articular corticosteroid injection and an oral nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug. The pain resolved after a few days, and the MRI repeated two weeks later showed a reduction in the size of the cystic collections and resolution of inflammatory changes.

Final Diagnosis:

Perforated cyst with a leak of its content into the soft tissue and mild to moderate joint effusion. 

Follow-up:

The patient is scheduled for a follow-up appointment to monitor the progress of the condition and ensure continued resolution of symptoms.

Discharge Summary:

Admission Date: 
Diagnosis: IgG4-related sialadenitis and IgM nephropathy

Hospital Course: 
The patient, a 55-year-old female, was admitted to our hospital with complaints of dry mouth and multiple missing teeth for several months. Urinalysis showed protein in the urine and IgG4-related sialadenitis was confirmed through pathological examination of labial gland biopsy tissue. IgM nephropathy was further diagnosed after renal biopsy. 

The patient was treated with prednisone and cyclophosphamide for 9 months which significantly improved her dry mouth symptoms. The patient's globulin, IgG levels, and cryoglobulin test returned to normal, and the levels of IgG4 and C3 and C4 significantly improved. 

The patient was discharged with follow-up appointments with rheumatology, nephrology, and ophthalmology departments for continued care and management of her condition. 

Instructions: 
1. Continue the prescribed medications as directed by the physician. 
2. Follow up with the rheumatology, nephrology, and ophthalmology departments per their recommendations. 
3. If any new symptoms or concerns arise, please contact the physician.

Considering the patient's medical history, family history, and clinical presentation, a clinical suspicion of MODY was raised. The patient was referred to Institut Pasteur in Tunis for genetic testing.

Summary:

The patient was a 21-year-old female with short stature, low BMI, and intellectual disability. Her laboratory results were consistent with diabetes, and she had a family history of the disease. She was referred to Institut Pasteur in Tunis for further evaluation.

Hospital Course:
The patient is a 39-year-old white non-Hispanic woman of Ashkenazi descent who presented with focal dystonia characterized by bilateral blepharoclonus on eyelid closure, sequelae from a prior right-sided Bell’s palsy, and mildly elevated tone in both arms. She had a history of acute dystonic reaction to ondansetron, acute akathisia to prochlorperazine, and more recently, akathisia to metoclopramide. There was also a family history of similar reactions on the paternal side.
Diagnosis:
Pharmacogenomic testing revealed the patient was heterozygous for the *41 allele (CYP2D6 2988G>A, NM_000106.6:c.985+39G>A, rs28371725), an intronic polymorphism associated with aberrant splicing of CYP2D6 leading to the skipping of exon 6 with a corresponding reduction in activity. This variant is responsible for the intermediate metabolizer phenotype in the majority of people of European descent.
Treatment:
The patient was started on appropriate medications for the dystonia and was referred to genetic counseling for further evaluation of her pharmacogenomic testing results. She was discharged in stable condition with follow-up arranged with her primary care provider.

Discharge Summary:

Chief Complaint:
Disequilibrium and object spinning sensation accompanied by vagal symptoms.

Hospital Course: 
The patient, a 24-year-old woman, presented with an acute vestibular deficit in the right ear, which led to a grade II spontaneous nystagmus towards the left without gaze fixation. The patient was administered diazepam i.v., which showed an improvement in her symptoms but led to the discovery of Hb 7.3 g/dL, Leukocytes 572 × 109/L, platelets 348 × 109/L, PT 57, TTPA 43.7, and D-dimer 2.13. A peripheral blood smear revealed 5% of myeloid blasts, one erythroblast per 100 cells, and giant platelets. She was referred to the department of hematology, where she was diagnosed with CML and leukostasis syndrome, which led to treatment with hydration, allopurinol, and emergency leukapheresis. The patient was discharged on the ninth day of hospitalization with leukocyte levels of 12 × 109/L. The VNG conducted later revealed a right vestibular deficit of 69%.

Post-Hospital Course:
The patient underwent audiometry and VNG, which showed normal hearing and a vestibular deficit of 69%, respectively. She will continue her follow-up with the ENT department. 

Diagnosis:
Chronic Myeloid Leukemia (CML) and Leukostasis Syndrome.

Condition at Discharge:
The patient was discharged with improved general symptoms with a grade II nystagmus without fixation towards the left side. 

Instructions:
Follow-up with the ENT department for monitoring and management of symptoms.

A 6-year-old male with MPS VI was admitted to our hospital after experiencing a transient tetraparesis following a minor fall. Discharge Summary

Patient: 66-year-old male with a past medical history of well-controlled diabetes and high cholesterol

Diagnosis: Organizing pneumonia

Hospital course:

The patient presented with progressive shortness of breath, dry cough, weight loss and night sweats. Initial treatment for severe community-acquired pneumonia was unsuccessful and he rapidly progressed to respiratory failure requiring mechanical ventilation. Diagnostic tests were performed, ruling out possible infections and connective tissue diseases. A CT-guided lung biopsy and VATs were done, ultimately leading to a diagnosis of organizing pneumonia. The patient was started on a systemic steroid course which resulted in remarkable improvement in his breathing and oxygen requirement. He was finally liberated from the ventilator and switched to oral prednisone. His condition continued to improve steadily over the hospitalization and was later discharged with a decreased dose of oral prednisone.

Follow-up:

His follow-up CT showed resolution of the micronodular infiltration. He is currently doing well clinically at 2 years post-hospitalization. 

Discharge medications:

The patient was discharged with oral prednisone. 

Recommendations:

Follow up with primary care physician.

Patient Name: [REDACTED]
Date of Admission: [REDACTED]

Hospital Course:
This 59-year-old female patient was admitted with a seizure in 2012. She had a medical history of hypertension and was diagnosed with a PPID after a 4.2x3.2x3.8 cm sized pineal region tumor was removed. The patient underwent adjuvant radiotherapy and was regularly monitored through follow-up MRIs.

In April 2018, multiple extra-axial masses were found in the patient's brain and the spinal MRI showed leptomeningeal involvement. The left parietal lobe mass was successfully removed and adjuvant therapy was administered. The patient responded well and was monitored regularly.

In October 2019, a new mass was discovered in the right middle cerebellar peduncle. The patient underwent hypofractionated SRS therapy, which was effective and well-tolerated.

Overall, the patient responded well to treatment and displayed no adverse effects or toxicities. Follow-up imaging showed stable enhancements and a complete response in some areas.

Discharge Diagnosis:
PPID - World Health Organization (WHO) grades II-III

Discharge Instructions:
The patient should continue to undergo regular follow-up MRIs. In case of any new symptoms or concerns, the patient should contact their healthcare provider immediately.

Follow-Up Care:
The patient will continue to receive regular follow-up imaging and consultations with their healthcare provider.

Patient Name: [Redacted]
Medical Record Number: [Redacted]
Admission Date: [Redacted]
Discharge Date: [Redacted]

Hospital Course Summary:

Admission Diagnosis: Acute kidney injury

Course: This 67-year-old woman with lung adenocarcinoma and a history of three lines of chemotherapy, including platinum salt, presented with acute kidney injury after receiving nivolumab treatment. At admission, the patient exhibited fatigue, nausea, and mild proteinuria. Renal biopsy showed severe interstitial nephritis with infiltration of inflammatory cells and granulomatosis, while immunological tests were negative except for positive antinuclear antibodies at low levels. The patient received oral steroids and nivolumab was withdrawn. On day-220, serum creatinine had improved to 124 μmol l−1.

Discharge Diagnosis: Acute kidney injury secondary to nivolumab treatment

Treatment: The patient was treated with oral steroids and nivolumab was definitively withdrawn.

Follow-up Plan: The patient will require continued monitoring and regular follow-up to evaluate renal function and manage any potential recurrence of acute kidney injury. Consultation with a nephrologist may be necessary.

Summary: This 67-year-old woman with lung adenocarcinoma presented with acute kidney injury after receiving nivolumab treatment. She was treated with oral steroids and nivolumab was withdrawn. Renal function improved and she was discharged with a follow-up plan for continued monitoring.

History of Present Illness:

A 65-year-old female patient was admitted to our department due to a recently diagnosed LA mass. She had been experiencing fever, malaise, and myalgia for five months. The patient had a previous diagnosis of ventricular septal defect (VSD) two years prior to admission.

Hospital Course:

The patient underwent surgical treatment during her hospital stay. The LA cyst attached to the interatrial septum was widely excised, and the atrial septum defect was closed with an artificial patch. The small VSD was closed with two pledgeted sutures without a patch.
